english:
  title: Record of Sobae Cave
  author: Jung Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: I came to lodge at the home of Hwang Yeon in Sobae Cave. The hamlet belonged to Naju, occupying what was once a garrison settlement at Geopyeong, named for the Buddhist temple Sobae that graces it. To the north, ridges upon ridges descend in succession; to the southwest, the lesser peaks open toward distant vistas. Below, in the southern reaches, spreads a broad plain where smoke rises from scattered homes—a dozen or so thatched dwellings of Hoeijin County. Among the renowned peaks nearby stands Geumseong Mountain, weighty and magnificent, guardian of the northeast and Naju's tutelary peak. Wolchul Mountain rises clear and bold to the southeast, marking the boundary with Yeongam. The Geumgang River flows from Naju's eastern reaches, passes through Hoeijin County, and merges with the sea to the southwest. The cave lies tens of miles inland. Mountain mists and sea vapors invade the skin, sickness comes unbidden—yet each dawn and dusk transforms the atmosphere into ten thousand visions worth beholding. The cave harbors no exotic flora; only golden reeds and slender bamboo mingle among pine and zelkova. In the homes, bamboo replaces timber for gates and fences, lending the whole a graceful, austere beauty that draws even distant hearts to settle and find peace. The people are simple and unambitious, content to labor in their fields. Hwang Yeon exemplifies this spirit. His household brews fine wine, and he loves to drink—whenever a batch ripens, he invites me first to share it. When guests arrive, he never fails to set out wine; with time, his courtesy only deepens. There was a man named Kim Seong-gil who knew letters well; his younger brother Cheon excelled at wit and humor, both devoted to drinking, brothers dwelling as one household. One Seo An-gil, grown old, became a monk called An-sim—high-nosed, long-faced, strange in countenance and bearing, yet he recalls every local dialect, saying, and matter of village life. There were also Kim Cheon-bu and Cho Song, drinkers of the same caliber as Seong-gil and Yeon. Daily they visited, and whenever the season brought me local delicacies, they would arrive bearing wine and refreshments, departing only after we had made merry together. I wore a single coat in winter, linen in summer. I slept early and rose late, unbound by routine, eating as appetite dictated. Between scholarly conversations with two or three learned companions, I would wind through streams and clamber over rocky ravines. When weary, I rested; when inspired, I wandered. Upon encountering beauty, I lingered, gazing and humming verses until the thought of home vanished. Sometimes I met a farmer or village elder, and we would sit on brushwood, offering each other comfort as friends of old. One day, ascending the rear hill, I beheld the western slope gently sloping toward broad fields below. I ordered a servant to clear the withered brush and had constructed a small dwelling of two rooms. The thatch remained uncut, the timber unhewn; I raised earth for steps and wove reeds into a fence. Simple work, minimal effort—yet all the villagers came to help, and in mere days it stood complete. I hung a plaque naming it the Thatched Cottage, and made it my home. Alas, when Du Fu dwelt in Chengdu, he built his Thatched Hall and resided there but briefly, yet its name echoes through a thousand years. How long shall I inhabit this cottage? After I depart, will wind and rain scatter it to ruin? Will wildfire consume it until nothing remains but dust? Or shall it be remembered by those who come after? I cannot know. I only know that I, mad and forthright, cast aside by the world, banished to exile in these distant hills—and yet the villagers receive me with such generosity. Perhaps they pity my poverty and offer shelter? Or perhaps, having grown distant from the capital's whispered judgments, they know not that I am condemned? In any measure, their kindness knows no bounds. I am at once ashamed and deeply moved. Therefore I record these circumstances, setting down what my heart cannot otherwise express.
  footnotes:
    - Du Fu (杜子美), the great Tang poet, famously built his Thatched Hall (草堂) in Chengdu where he lived during political exile. It became one of the most celebrated symbols of literary retreat in Chinese tradition.
    - Jung Do-jeon was exiled from court and lived in the Sobae area during a period of political disgrace before his later rehabilitation.
